ce:section.ce:para:
Heteroatom doped-CDs, especially doped with nitrogen, are widely used as corrosion inhibitors for copper and its alloy. In 2019, Qiang et al. [42] prepared a novel N-doped CDs (NCDs) with 4-Aminosalicylic acid as a precursor through a facile hydrothermal method and evaluated the anticorrosion performance of copper in the aggressive H2SO4 medium. The morphology of the NCDs revealed a nearly spherical shape and a uniform distribution in size (∼3 nm) (Fig. 1
                           a and b). From the high-resolution XPS spectra (C1s, N1s, O1s) of NCDs (Fig. 1c and e), two peaks of the C1s at 284.9 and 286.1 eV, associated with C=C and C–O/C–N groups, respectively (Fig. 1c). The N1s signals at 399.1 and 400.0 eV were attributed to the form of C–N–C and (C)3–N, respectively (Fig. 1d). These results clearly confirmed that nitrogen atoms have been successfully doped into the CDs. Raman and FT-IR techniques were further used to characterize the NCDs and gave a similar result. Weight loss (gravimetric/mass loss) measurement and electrochemical techniques including potentiodynamic polarization (PDP) and electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) were used to evaluate the corrosion resistance of the prepared NCDs. The Tafel curve indicated that NCDs was a modest cathodic-type inhibitor and the IE value increased with increasing NCDs concentration. The IE value was close to 90.6% for 50 mg/L at 298 K. The diameter of high-frequency loop increased when introducing the NCDs and continuously became enlarged with increasing NCDs concentration. This result suggested that an adsorbed NCDs film was formed and thus inhibited the charge transfer process (Fig. 2
                           ). The formation of the NCDs-adsorption film on copper substrate responsible for the superior inhibition performance was also supported by surface morphological observation and EDS analysis. The formed protective film followed a Langmuir adsorption model. A mixed interaction involves chemisorption and physisorption was confirmed at the copper/solution interface and the chemisorption played the major role.

Recently, Guo et al. used FCDs/BNNS nanocomposite for enhancing corrosion resistance of waterborne epoxy coating to protect copper metal [61]. The amino-functionalized carbon dots (FCDs) were used as intercalators to exfoliate and modify the boron nitride to prepare the FCDs/boron nitride nanosheets (BNNS) nanocomposite. Then FCDs/BNNS were blended into the waterborne epoxy (WEP) matrix to prepare the corresponding WEP/CD composite coatings on the copper (Fig. 13
                        a). Among all the tested samples, the as-obtained WEP/CD composite coating showed the optimal corrosion protection performance even after 40 d immersion in 3.5 wt% NaCl solution. EIS results indicated that the impedance value (4.97 × 105 Ω cm2) of WEP/CD composite coating was significantly higher than that of the control sample (3.36 × 104 Ω cm2). LEIS technique was used to further analyse the local corrosion situation and corresponding results were shown in Fig. 13 b-e. Among all the tested samples, the impedance value for WEP coating is the lowest (Fig. 13b), suggesting the poorest protective performance of WEP coating. The impedance value increased by about an order of magnitude after adding FCDs, BNNS or FCDs/BNNS into the WEP coatings, implying the improvement of corrosion protection ability (Fig. 13c–e). The average surface-distribution impedance values for WEP FCDs/BNNS coating are higher than those for WEP FCDs and BNNS coating (Fig. 13e), indicating the highest corrosion protection efficiency. FCDs intercalated between BNNS and thus greatly weakened the interlayer force, which resulted in a recued the aggregation and an improvement of the dispersity in the WEP coating. The excellent anticorrosive ability was benefited from the following factors (Fig. 14
                        ): (1) BNNS as a physical barrier prolonged the diffusion path of corrosive species and reduced the inherent defects of the composite coating, thus retarded the corrosion rate. (2) FCDs could act as the effective corrosion inhibitors and was strongly adsorbed on the exposed or corroded copper surface to hinder the further corrosion. Physical barrier performance from BNNS and self-healing capability from FCDs synergistically make the composite coating with excellent corrosion resistance.
